{{Quote|The current debate stems over which zero-point year-notation system is the best, with the Great ReSynchronization of 13 years ago and the Ruusan Reformation of a millennium ago being popular contenders.|[[HoloNet News/Legends|HoloNet News]]|<ref name="HNN 45">{{HoloNetNewsWeb|45|life/13228_2.html|RM&S; Debates Calendar Reform}}</ref>}}
The '''Great ReSynchronization''' was a reform of the [[Galactic Standard Calendar]] that was adopted in [[35 BBY/Legends|35 BBY]] by the [[Republic Measures & Standards Bureau]] to recalibrate the disparate dating systems used by the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]].<ref name="HNN 45" /> The reform established the year 35 BBY as the zero point of the [[Great ReSynchronization calendar|new calendar]].<ref name="HNN 45" /><ref name="SWC">{{Blog|danwallace|3|Star Wars Calendars}}</ref>

==Behind the scenes==
The dating scheme for the Great ReSynchronization calendar was introduced in [[West End Games]]' ''[[Star Wars Adventure Journal]]'' for its recurring in-universe articles ''[[Galaxywide NewsNets]]''. This dating system used the year 35 BBY at its zero point,<ref name="GNN3">{{JournalCite|3|Galaxywide NewsNets}}</ref> which the [[1994]] reference book ''[[A Guide to the Star Wars Universe, Second Edition, Revised and Expanded]]'' established as the end of the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]].<ref name="AGttSWU">''[[A Guide to the Star Wars Universe, Second Edition, Revised and Expanded]]''</ref> As later sources placed the Clone Wars one decade later,<ref name="AotC">{{Film|II}}</ref> [[Pablo Hidalgo]]'s ''[[HoloNet News (original website)|HoloNet News]]'' eventually [[Retroactive continuity|retconned]] the year 35 BBY as the Great ReSynchronization to justify its use as a calendar zero point.<ref name="HNN 45" /><ref name="SWC" />

